<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-08-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-08-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="17" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 17.</note>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Geo. H. Yeaman</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Fish</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 255.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United
                                        States,</hi><hi rend="italic"> Copenhagen</hi></placeName>,
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-08-13"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 13, 1870</date>. (Received August 30,
                                1870.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Marquis de Cadore left here yesterday,
                            and if he accomplished anything while here, it is wholly unknown, and it
                            is believed that he did not. There can now be no further question about
                            the neutrality of Denmark until the tide of war turns as decidedly in
                            favor of France as it has so far been in favor of Prussia.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>GEO. H. YEAMAN.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>